\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Communication Authority and the One Voice Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy establishes the One Voice Rule for cybersecurity incident communications.
 The One Voice Rule requires that all strategic,
 public-facing,
 and external incident communications be authorized by the Incident Commander and issued through a single authoritative channel.
 This rule is consistent with the broader communications governance established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.14"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and is restated here in operational terms for personnel and external reviewers who may not have access to the full ECIO Policy Manual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director,
 serving as Incident Commander by default under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 shall be the sole authoritative source for strategic and public-facing messaging during a cybersecurity incident.
 When IC authority has been delegated to a Tier L3+ technical lead in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 the delegate shall exercise communication authorization authority within the scope of that delegation.
 The IT Director shall retain personal authority over NRS 603A.220 breach notifications,
 media and public statements,
 and law enforcement referral communications regardless of IC delegation status.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IC shall authorize all external communications before issuance.
 No Information Operations personnel shall issue,
 publish,
 or transmit any external communication regarding a cybersecurity incident without prior IC authorization,
 except where the technical coordination carve-out defined in Section 6.7 applies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The One Voice Rule shall not prohibit internal communication necessary for incident response coordination.
 Internal status communications among IT Department personnel do not require individual IC authorization,
 but shall comply with the documentation requirements in Section 6.11 and the speculation prohibition in Section 3 of this policy.
\end_layout

