\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 NRS 603A.220 Breach Notification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
NRS 603A.220 requires notification to affected individuals following discovery of a breach of personal information.
 The statute directs that disclosure be made "in the most expedient time possible and without unreasonable delay." This section establishes the Department's internal performance standards that operationalize that statutory obligation with measurable timelines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Breach Determination:

\series default
 The IT Director shall render a formal breach determination within twenty-four (24) hours of the IC confirming that conditions meeting the statutory definition of a breach under NRS 603A.220 have been identified.
 A formal breach determination is a documented finding,
 rendered by the IT Director on the basis of the evidence available at the time,
 that personal information has been acquired by an unauthorized person or that acquisition is supported by one (1) or more of the following indicators:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Direct evidence of unauthorized access to a system,
 account,
 or data store containing personal information,
 including but not limited to authenticated session records,
 access logs,
 or forensic artifacts showing read,
 copy,
 or export activity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Evidence of exfiltration,
 including but not limited to outbound network transfers to unauthorized destinations,
 staged data repositories,
 or confirmed data transmission to a threat actor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Unauthorized acquisition of physical media or devices known to contain personal information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Credential compromise combined with authentication records showing successful access to systems containing personal information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Threat actor communications,
 including ransom demands or extortion messages,
 referencing specific personal information held by the County.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall document in the incident work order and the Chapter 4 checklist:
 the specific indicators relied upon,
 the evidence supporting each indicator,
 the categories of personal information affected,
 and the basis for the determination.
 Absence of an indicator on this list does not preclude a breach determination when the totality of evidence supports the finding;
 the IT Director shall document the alternative basis in that case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
When IC authority has been delegated under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 the delegate shall escalate any condition that may constitute a breach to the IT Director immediately upon identification.
 The IT Director shall retain sole authority over the breach determination regardless of IC delegation status.
 This constraint operates in addition to the Directed Deputization non-delegable list in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Notification Preparation:

\series default
 The IT Director shall ensure that a draft breach notification is prepared within forty-eight (48) hours of the breach determination.
 The Assistant IT Director shall include in the draft,
 at minimum,
 the nature of the breach in general terms,
 the categories of personal information affected,
 the approximate date of the breach,
 a description of actions taken by the Department in response,
 and contact information for affected individuals to obtain further information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Legal Review:

\series default
 The IT Director shall submit the draft breach notification to the District Attorney's Office for legal review prior to issuance in accordance with the mandatory routing requirements in Section 6.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Issuance Timeline:

\series default
 The IT Director shall issue the breach notification to affected individuals within five (5) business days of the breach determination,
 or upon completion of the District Attorney's Office legal review,
 whichever is later.
 Under no circumstance shall the IT Director issue breach notification later than ten (10) business days from the date of the breach determination.
 These timelines are ECIO internal performance standards and do not override any delay expressly permitted by NRS 603A.220,
 including a law enforcement determination under NRS 603A.220(3) that notification would impede a criminal investigation.
 When a law enforcement hold is in effect,
 the IT Director shall document the hold in the incident work order and shall issue the breach notification after the law enforcement agency determines that notification will not compromise the investigation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Method of Notification:

\series default
 The IT Director shall deliver notification by written notice sent to the most recent address on file for each affected individual,
 or by electronic notice if the affected individual has consented to electronic communication,
 consistent with NRS 603A.220.
 If the cost of providing individual notice exceeds two hundred fifty thousand dollars ($250,000),
 or the affected class exceeds five hundred thousand (500,000) persons,
 or the Department does not have sufficient contact information,
 the IT Director shall provide substitute notice in accordance with the substitute notice provisions of NRS 603A.220.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Documentation:

\series default
 The IT Director shall document the following in the incident work order:
 the breach determination and its basis,
 the date the draft notification was prepared,
 the date the draft was submitted for legal review,
 the date legal review was completed,
 the date notification was issued,
 the method of notification,
 the number of individuals notified,
 and the categories of personal information affected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 External Partner Engagement Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The ECIO maintains relationships with external entities that provide threat intelligence,
 incident coordination resources,
 and law enforcement support during cybersecurity incidents.
 All external partner engagement during an active incident shall require IC authorization and shall be executed within the One Voice Rule and communication authorization framework established in Section 6.1.
 The IC shall authorize partner engagement based on the functional category of support required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Threat Intelligence Support:

\series default
 The IC may initiate contact with the Multi-State Information Sharing and Analysis Center (MS-ISAC) or the Nevada Information Sharing and Analysis Center (NV-ISAC) to request threat intelligence,
 indicator sharing,
 or analytical support relevant to the incident.
 The IC may delegate initiation of threat intelligence requests to a designee authorized under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The IC or designee shall limit information shared with threat intelligence partners to the technical indicators and environmental context necessary to support the request.
 The IC or designee shall not share organizational identifiers,
 PII,
 or CJI with threat intelligence partners without explicit IT Director authorization and compliance with the data handling requirements established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Coordination:

\series default
 The IC may request incident coordination support from the MS-ISAC,
 NV-ISAC,
 or other entities with relevant capability when the scope or complexity of an incident exceeds internal capacity.
 The IT Director shall authorize incident coordination engagement.
 The IT Director shall define the scope of information authorized for sharing with the coordinating entity at the time of engagement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Law Enforcement Referral:

\series default
 The IT Director shall determine whether an incident warrants law enforcement referral to the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) or the Nevada Department of Public Safety (DPS).
 The IT Director shall make law enforcement referral decisions personally.
 The IT Director shall not delegate law enforcement referral authority.
 The IT Director shall ensure that the communication is routed through the District Attorney's Office in accordance with Section 6.8 prior to initiating law enforcement referral.
 The IT Director shall document the referral decision,
 the basis for the decision,
 and the date and substance of any law enforcement contact in the incident work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Documentation:

\series default
 The IC or designee shall document all external partner communications in the incident work order within four (4) hours of the communication.
 The documentation shall include the date and time,
 the partner entity contacted,
 the individual contacted,
 the method of contact,
 the substance of the communication,
 and the scope of information shared.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Technical Coordination and Vendor Communication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The One Voice Rule shall not prohibit technical staff from communicating operational and technical details to vendors,
 service providers,
 or managed service partners when necessary to resolve an active incident.
 This carve-out is subject to the following guardrails.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Permitted Scope:

\series default
 Technical coordination communications shall be limited to the technical actions required to resolve the immediate condition.
 Technical staff may describe symptoms,
 share log data,
 request vendor support actions,
 and coordinate remediation steps within the scope of the vendor's service responsibility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Restricted Topics During Breach:

\series default
 During a confirmed or suspected breach involving personal information or Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 Information Operations personnel shall not discuss the following topics with vendors or external parties without explicit IC authorization:
 the scope or magnitude of the breach,
 the nature or volume of affected data,
 PII or CJI involvement or exposure,
 incident attribution or suspected threat actor identity,
 and any information that could affect the Department's legal position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
IC Notification:

\series default
 Information Operations personnel who initiate external technical communication during an active incident shall notify the IC within one (1) hour of the initiation of the communication.
 The notifying personnel shall include in the notification the vendor or partner contacted,
 the purpose of the communication,
 and a summary of information shared.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Documentation:

\series default
 Information Operations personnel shall summarize all technical coordination communications in the incident work order within four (4) hours of the communication.
 The summary shall include the date and time,
 the vendor or partner contacted,
 the technical substance discussed,
 and any actions requested or committed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Data Handling:

\series default
 All technical coordination communications shall comply with the data classification and handling requirements established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Information Operations personnel shall not transmit restricted data via unencrypted channels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.8 Legal Review Routing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall submit the following categories of incident-related communications to the District Attorney's Office for legal review prior to issuance.
 Submission to the District Attorney's Office does not transfer communication authority;
 the IT Director retains authorization authority over all communications under this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Mandatory Legal Review Triggers:
\series default

\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All NRS 603A.220 breach notifications to affected individuals or the public.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All media and public communications regarding a cybersecurity incident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All communications to regulatory bodies outside the CJIS notification chain,
 including state agencies,
 the Attorney General's Office,
 or other regulatory authorities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All communications associated with an incident where law enforcement referral is being considered or has occurred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS Notification Exclusion:

\series default
 CJIS IR-6 Part (b) notifications to the CSO,
 SIB Chief,
 or Interface Agency Official shall not require District Attorney's Office review prior to issuance.
 These notifications are a compliance obligation with defined notification windows,
 and inserting additional review steps could jeopardize execution within the notification windows established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Submission:

\series default
 The IT Director shall submit the draft communication to the District Attorney's Office with a summary of the incident context,
 the communication type,
 and the urgency of issuance.
 The IT Director shall document the date and time of submission in the incident work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Completion:

\series default
 Upon receipt of the District Attorney's Office review,
 the IT Director shall incorporate any required modifications.
 The IT Director shall document the completion of legal review in the incident work order,
 including the date of completion and a summary of any modifications made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Escalation for Non-Response:

\series default
 If the District Attorney's Office does not respond within three (3) business days of submission for a breach notification review under Section 6.5,
 the IT Director shall escalate the non-response to the County Manager and shall proceed with issuance of the original draft notification within the ten (10) business day ceiling established in Section 6.5.
 The IT Director shall document the escalation,
 the absence of completed legal review,
 and the basis for proceeding in the incident work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.9 Media and Public Communications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall serve as the sole authorized spokesperson for all media and public communications regarding a cybersecurity incident.
 The IT Director shall not delegate media or public communication authority.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall not issue any media or public communication without prior legal review in accordance with Section 6.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
No Information Operations personnel shall respond to media inquiries,
 issue public statements,
 post to social media,
 or otherwise communicate with the public regarding a cybersecurity incident without the IT Director's explicit written authorization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall ensure that media and public communications do not include speculation regarding incident cause,
 attribution,
 scope,
 or data compromise.
 The IT Director shall limit such communications to confirmed facts that have been reviewed and authorized for public release.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall coordinate media and public communications with the County Manager prior to issuance.
 The IT Director shall provide the County Manager,
 at minimum,
 advance notice of the communication content and timing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.10 Post-Incident and Post-Handback Communications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Upon declaration of Operational Handback under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Recovery Operations and Restoration Prioritization),
 the IT Director shall issue the following post-incident communications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Incident Closure Notification:

\series default
 The IT Director shall notify the County Manager and any previously notified stakeholders that the incident has been closed and Operational Handback has been completed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Postmortem Data Consolidation:

\series default
 The Assistant IT Director shall compile all communication records produced under this policy — including internal status updates,
 external notifications,
 partner engagement documentation,
 legal review records,
 and media communications — and shall prepare the compiled records for inclusion in the postmortem under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The Assistant IT Director shall include all pertinent communication data,
 regardless of source,
 in both the internal and external postmortem reports.
 The Assistant IT Director shall apply data protection controls appropriate to the classification of the information under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 to the postmortem record.
 The Assistant IT Director shall handle PII,
 CJI,
 and restricted data in accordance with the applicable data protection requirements,
 including redaction where necessary to protect affected individuals in externally distributed postmortem materials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS Closure Notification:

\series default
 If CJIS IR-6 Part (b) external notification was executed during the incident,
 the IT Director (as LASO) shall notify the CSO,
 SIB Chief,
 or Interface Agency Official of incident closure.
 The IT Director (as LASO) shall include in the closure notification the date of Operational Handback and a summary of the incident outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.11 Communication Documentation and Data Protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Documentation Standard:

\series default
 The IC shall ensure that all incident-related communications produced under this policy are documented in the incident work order maintained in the System of Engagement.
 The documentation timeframe for each communication type is specified in Section 6.2.
 Where a communication type specifies documentation "at the time of issuance," the responsible personnel shall enter the documentation into the work order before the end of the business day on which the communication was issued,
 or by 10:00 AM on the following business day if the communication was issued within the final two (2) hours of the business day.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Verbal and Informal Communications:

\series default
 Information Operations personnel shall summarize verbal or informal communications — including phone calls,
 hallway conversations,
 and instant messages — that pertain to an active cybersecurity incident and shall enter the summary into the incident work order within four (4) hours of the communication.
 This four-hour standard supersedes the one (1) business day standard established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 for non-incident operations for the duration of active incident response.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Privileged Communications:

\series default
 Communications subject to attorney-client privilege — including the substance of legal review exchanges with the District Attorney's Office — shall not be documented in the System of Engagement work order.
 The IC shall record only metadata in the work order:
 the date of submission,
 the date of completion,
 and the fact that legal review occurred.
 The District Attorney's Office shall retain privileged substance under its own direction and in accordance with its own records management obligations.
 This carve-out does not exempt the IT Director from documenting the outcome of legal review (modifications made,
 approval to proceed) in the work order;
 it protects only the privileged substance of the attorney-client exchange itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Private Note Usage:

\series default
 The Private Note constraints established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 apply to incident work order documentation under this policy.
 Information Operations personnel shall use Private Notes only for the authorized purposes defined in that section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Data Classification Compliance:

\series default
 All incident-related communications shall comply with the data classification and handling requirements established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Information Operations personnel shall not transmit restricted data — including PII,
 CJI,
 and security vulnerability details — via unencrypted email,
 public file shares,
 or other unprotected channels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Public Records Awareness:

\series default
 Information Operations personnel shall compose incident-related written communications with the awareness that such records may be subject to disclosure under NRS 239 (Public Records),
 unless protected by a specific statutory exemption or confidentiality requirement.
 This awareness requirement is established at the governance level in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.14"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and is restated here for external readers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.12 Incident Response Contact Directory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall ensure that the Department maintains an incident response contact directory — a living reference document that identifies current personnel assigned to incident response roles,
 their contact information,
 and the escalation sequence to be followed during an active incident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Required Contact Categories:

\series default
 The Administrative Assistant shall ensure that the contact directory includes,
 at minimum,
 the following categories:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
IT Department personnel with incident response role assignments,
 including the IT Director,
 Assistant IT Director,
 and all personnel authorized to serve as Incident Commander.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
County Manager and administrative leadership contacts for executive notification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
District Attorney's Office contact for legal review routing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Elko County Emergency Manager contact for coordination during incidents affecting county-wide operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
CJIS notification contacts:
 the CSO,
 the SIB Chief,
 and the Interface Agency Official.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
External partner contacts:
 the MS-ISAC,
 the NV-ISAC,
 the FBI field office,
 and the Nevada DPS point of contact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Vendor and managed service provider emergency contacts for Tier 1 Mission Critical services and Security Infrastructure as classified under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Service Continuity and Contingency Planning Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Media and public affairs contacts,
 including the County's designated media liaison if applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Operational Maintenance:

\series default
 The Administrative Assistant shall maintain the contact directory as a governed Knowledge Base artifact in the System of Engagement in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The actual contact details are operational data and shall not appear in this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Physical Copy Distribution:

\series default
 The Administrative Assistant shall maintain current physical copies of the contact directory at distribution points designated by the IT Director,
 including at minimum the IT Department and locations accessible to the County Manager and County Emergency Manager when the System of Engagement is unavailable.
 The incident response contact directory is designated for physical distribution to ensure accessibility during an active incident when electronic systems may be compromised or unavailable.
 This requirement is established by this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Validation Cadence:

\series default
 The Administrative Assistant shall prepare annual validation data for the contact directory,
 confirming that all listed personnel remain in their assigned roles,
 that contact information is current,
 and that the escalation sequence reflects the current organizational structure.
 The IT Director shall review the validation data and render the annual validation determination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
Immediate Update Obligation:

\series default
 The Administrative Assistant shall update the contact directory within one (1) business day of any personnel change affecting an IR role assignment.
 Personnel changes include new hires,
 separations,
 role transfers,
 and changes to contact information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\lang english
IC Designation Records:

\series default
 Incident Commander designation records created during an active incident shall be maintained separately from the contact directory,
 in the incident record at the time of designation,
 in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The contact directory identifies personnel eligible for IC designation;
 the incident record documents who was actually designated for a specific incident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.13 Communication Record Retention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Communication records produced under this policy — including work order documentation of all communication types defined in Section 6.2,
 CJIS notification log entries,
 breach notification records,
 external partner communication logs,
 legal review submission and completion records,
 and media communication records — shall be retained for three (3) calendar years from the end of the calendar year in which the incident was closed.
 This retention period is consistent with LRDA 20071728 (IT Security Audit Records) and exceeds the CJIS AU-11 one-year minimum for audit records.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Communication records that form part of the incident record maintained under 
\series bold
Policy 
